SIMIAN VIRUSES, POTENTIAL FOR HUMAN INFECTION (02)
**************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Simian viruses, potential for human infection 980405151802
[1
Date: Mon, 6 Apr 1998 07:47:36 -0400
From: Ronald Gold <rongold@netcom.ca>

Live SV40 virus was present in both OPV and IPV used prior to 1963. [OPV =
oral polio vaccine, IPV = injectable polio vaccine.
Information presented at the NIH Conference on SIV40 in January, 1997
included the following:
1. Live RSV [respiratory syncytial virus used in challenge studies in
volunteers in late 1950s contained live SV40 [because it was grown in
monkey tissue culture. The nasal inoculum contained 10 000 TCID50 doses
of SV40 [TCID50 = 50% tissue culture infectious doses. Moderate elevation
of neutralizing antibody titers occurred in 70% and 30% recipients [sic
with shedding [of SV40 in the throat for 1-2 weeks.
2. OPV vaccine with high titer SV40 did not induce any antibody response in
recipients. Stool cultures [were positive for up to 5 weeks in 30%,
indicating some replication in intestinal tract occurred.
3. Lab workers with close contact with infected rhesus monkeys: 50-60% have
anti-SV40 neutralizing antibody.
Fortunately, there is no evidence that SV40 causes harm in humans.
--
Ronald Gold
e-mail: rongold@netcom.ca
